Article by Faust from 2002
(1/2)
Everyone Knows the deceased Dead and Euronymous; either by name, reputation or activities. These people are by many claimed to be the originators of what has turned into a vivid and extensive Black Metal Underground Movement; an honor they serve through the fact that their lives and also post-existence ensured to gather the complexities of the once so weak and tiny scene, elaborating the basic principles and put it to practice.

These two persons are by many also claimed to be the real Mayhem, what constituted Mayhem in effect. Euronymous had from the beginning engendered and ensured Mayhem’s music and riffing, from the chaotic and crushing music that could be found in their Deathcrush-era to the atmospheric yet intensely brutal sonic metal towards their De Mysteriis Dom Sathanas-era.

Dead, with his haunting vocals, made the listener imagine an audio-trip to the lost castles of Transylvania while at the same time giving the impression of just having risen from the grave. Dead lived up to his pseudonym - and he should live even more up to it than anyone would like to imagine.

The last time I ever met Euronymous was in his flat in Toyen, Oslo, in early June 1993. I was at that time playing in Emperor and we were heading towards a mini-tour in England with Cradle of Filth. Euronymous had just closed down his shop, Helvete, as a result from massive media-pressure because of the criminal activities that rose to unexpected heights in the Norwegian Black Metal scene. The plan was to open the shop again in a more visited area of the city and therefore to ensure a bigger economical income. This night I visited Euronymous one last time before going to England and discussed a few matters with him. That was the last time I ever saw him alive.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114954598
(2/2)
Emperor returned from England about two weeks later; exhausted and sleepy but with a little broader horizon and richer experiences. I never met up with Euronymous again since I shortly lived at my father’s in the north-east of Norway, but I went to Oslo the 10th of August to visit him. The shock was enormous when I was in the middle of the police-investigation and was brought in for interrogation. I couldn’t imagine that anyone had killed Euronymous. I wont dwell with the details concerning his death, the people behind it or anything. It has nothing to do with this article. But it’s clear that from that point the scene had lost one of his main participants, and in my eyes, the scene would never be the same again. Unfortunately.

Dead died in April 1991, then fully completing and realizing his long-time band pseudonym. I appreciate very much that I got to get known with Dead the time he spent in Norway. He was indeed a strange personality. Posterior to his death; all kinds of myths have been made about him; he was really the personification of an evil madman, according to many. Well then let myths be myths and focus rather on reality as it appear in broad daylight. Dead was a nice man and Dead was a good man (a description many might find “blasphemous” but it still doesn’t hide the fact that Dead was a good man). He had his own little view of life, which was constituted by Transylvania, vultures, bats, grim trees (he often went into the woods to paint “grim trees”), graves and non-synthized Black Metal. In despite of his obsession, he was harmless and wanted to leave alone and be left alone.

I'm half Jewish, and I've read everything I can find about Roger Waters' politics, and I still don't see how he's anti-semitic. I'm supportive of Israel's existence because I think it's important to have a kind of Jewish safe haven after a history of persecution in Europe. However, it's effectively an apartheid state with racist policies. Palestinians need to have the same rights as any other citizens, and any invasive settlements should be dismantled.

I disagree with some of Waters' hyperbolic statements, but if he was truly anti-semitic I think he would've crossed over into anti-Jew rhetoric, and he never, ever has. Everything he's said is just critical of Israel's treatment of Palestinians. There are plenty of old celebrities who are bona fide antisemites, including Van Morrison, but as far as I can tell, Roger Waters isn't one of them. He's also the mind behind pretty much everything interesting Pink Floyd has done, at least since the departure of Syd Barrett.

Toby McKeehan's transition from dorky Beastie Boys white rapper to CCM's answer to Kurt Cobain in just 6 short years was interesting. That's one of the things with Christian music. >>114954365
Kryie is a great track, but I wouldn't consider them an overtly "Christian" act.
I do have to tentatively take back what I said though. CCM is derivative shit for the most part, but there's some competent overtly Christian artists I had forgotten about. Larry Norman, Keith Green, Phil Keaggy, Charlie Peacock, Steve Taylor (who wrote most of the lyrics for Newsboys during their heyday and fronted Chagall Guevara), Mutemath. There's others I'm forgetting. If you get outside the Christian book store CCM scene where you don't have to churn out happy clappy Jesus music to the tune of whatever the current Hot 100 is there's some meat there.
Interestingly, Kevin Max Smith of DC Talk has renounced Christianity, as have a bunch of other Christian artists/bands. The guy from As I Lay Dying said that back when they were touring, the vast majority of the Christian acts they played with were just doing happy clappy Jesus music for the bucks and almost none of them were actual practicing Christians. The modern entertainer lifestyle just doesn't jive well with Christianity.

part of the reason it's harder to find good korean music is because when rock was getting popular in korea, a punk band invited some friend idiots on a music show and they jumped around with their dongs out on public weekend TV. It was a major scandal and got the show it was on canceled and a big stigma grew around band music. Music Shows are a big part of how the public and international fans get exposed (kek) to new music, so it really kneecapped the growth. It's coming back now but it's taken like a decade.

This is the producer behind what was arguably the most successful kpop song of 2022 and one of the most successful songs of 2023 so far (Hype Boy and Ditto by NewJeans, respectively, both really good).
After working as a producer for big kpop groups for years he released his first solo album in 2022 (a few months before working with NewJeans).
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZHbnVPDsYX8
It's essentially a concept album that serves as an homage to ppongjjak (an energetic, over-the-top, extremely tacky subgenre of Korean techno/synth-pop music) and other similar subgenres. It's a fun listen.

>>114944564
You're ignoring the degradation of quality that happens when artists base their decision-making on what is classically seemed to be "correct" instead of their own intuitions about what works and what doesn't when it comes to their own personalized self-expression. Classical music is more developed because so many people were working in similar idioms for a very long time, but that doesn't mean any of it is inherently better - it could just as easily mean they were exploring one little pocket of a giant space of possibilities for an extremely long time, and that there are much more interesting and deeply resonant musical ideas to be found by the modern people who are now daring to step outside of that pocket. And unlike the composers of 200+ years ago, they aren't bound by the inherent limitations of "follow these rules and learn these things and then you can be a great composer." After all, someone had to invent those rules, and why should we assume they are never to be outdone?

>>114945486
Get something as a reference note (keyboard, recording, whatever) and tune one string to that note, let's say the low E string. Tune the A string by playing the 5th fret of the E string and matching the sound. Keep doing that for all the strings. Eventually you'll git good at recognizing whether something is sharp or flat, but not if you keep relying on tuners: it's something you have to train your ear for.

If it's an acoustic use anything that gives you a440hz or 432hz and then relative pitch

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>no answers suggesting harmonically tuning
Bunch of amateurs I see

Play the 5th fret harmonic on the E & 7th fret harmonic on the A at the same time. Repeat for A-D & D-G. Then the 7th fret harmonic on the E and the open B. Then 7th fret harmonic on the A and open high e.

They should all hum perfectly in these pairs. This method ensures you are tuning to the open position of the strings, without bending by pressing frets. It is vital the guitar has proper intonation, which will be obvious after tuning to this method. It is also vital 1 reference string is pitch matched to the correct hertz, else the instrument will be out and the different tension will result in poor intonation even if properly intonated.
